<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="353" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1357,1706]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1501,1526]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[324,490,1502,1526]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref3795" refString="Attems, C. (1937) Myriapoda 3 Polydesmoidea I Fam. Strongylosomidae. Das Tierreich, 68, 1 - 300." type="journal article">Attems (1937)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation box="[550,770,1501,1526]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref4448" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1952) Some American polydesmid millipeds in the collection of the Chicago MUseUm of NatUral History. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 45, 553 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 45.4.553" type="journal article">Chamberlin (1952)</bibRefCitation>
, who assigned 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brolemann" authorityYear="1898" box="[949,1104,1501,1525]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Aphelidesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[949,1104,1501,1525]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Aphelidesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to, now, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Strongylosomatidea)" authorityName="Strongylosomatidea" class="Diplopoda" family="Paradoxosomatidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplopoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Paradoxosomatidae (Strongylosomatidea)</taxonomicName>
, are the only authors to have placed the genus in a polydesmidan suborder other than Leptodesmidea (=Chelodesmidea). We suspect they did so because the cingula and acropodital divisions in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brolemann" authorityYear="1898" box="[151,307,1609,1633]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Aphelidesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,307,1609,1633]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Aphelidesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
convergently resemble those in 
<taxonomicName box="[669,891,1609,1634]" class="Diplopoda" family="Paradoxosomatidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplopoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Paradoxosomatidae</taxonomicName>
, which are generally associated with ambulatory podomeres. 
<bibRefCitation box="[294,463,1646,1670]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref3795" refString="Attems, C. (1937) Myriapoda 3 Polydesmoidea I Fam. Strongylosomidae. Das Tierreich, 68, 1 - 300." type="journal article">Attems (1937)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation box="[523,675,1645,1670]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref4929" refString="Jeekel, C. A. W. (1950) On some polydesmoid millipeds from SUrinam. Entomologische Berichten, 13, 70 - 76." type="journal article">Jeekel (1950</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation box="[692,750,1646,1670]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref5045" refString="Jeekel, C. A. W. (2000) Notes on Aphelidesmidae from GUiana. With the description of two new genera and three new species (Diplopoda. Polydesmida). Myriapod Memoranda, 2, 71 - 93." type="journal article">2000</bibRefCitation>
) labeled these divisions in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brolemann" authorityYear="1898" box="[1085,1241,1645,1669]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Aphelidesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1085,1241,1645,1669]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Aphelidesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but omitted the postfemur, so tibiotarsus follows the femur.
</paragraph>
